{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480916"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:53:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:53:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"125"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/125"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.26,0.09,0.08,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"125"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52850"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/125"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"125"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38233"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"100"},{"type":"tags","id":"763"},{"type":"tags","id":"2062"},{"type":"tags","id":"2100"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5932"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12615"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14978"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15187"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52850"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for pre-operative assessment. He is scheduled for an elective repair of a right inguinal hernia next week. He has a medical history of gastro-oesophageal reflux and hypercholesterolaemia, but is otherwise in good health. He does not take any regular medications. He is a non-smoker and drinks about one glass of wine a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His BMI is 28 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. The physical examination is otherwise unremarkable. Some consideration must be given to prophylaxis against venous thromboembolism. He will wear graded compression stockings and there will be intra-operative pneumatic calf compression.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate additional measure for thromboprophylaxis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No additional measures","Enoxaparin daily until discharge","Enoxaparin daily for ten days after the operation","Pneumatic calf compression until discharge","Graduated compression stockings and enoxaparin daily for ten days after the operation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is considered low-risk for venous thromboembolism (VTE) based on the Caprini Score, which is the most widely utilised and validated VTE risk assessment model for surgical patients. In this case, \u003Cstrong\u003Eno additional measures\u003C/strong\u003E beyond the planned mechanical prophylaxis are necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Caprini Score considers various risk factors, including age, type of surgery, recent medical events, venous disease, mobility, and other medical conditions. For this patient, the only identifiable risk factors are his male gender and BMI \u0026gt;25 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, which would likely place him in the low-risk category (1-2 points).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInterpretation of the Caprini model is as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVery low risk (\u0026lt;0.5%): 0 points\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELow risk (1.5%): 1-2 points\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EModerate risk (3%): 3-4 points\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHigh risk (\u0026gt;6%): \u22655 points\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin daily until discharge\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eenoxaparin daily for ten days after the operation\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive for this low-risk patient undergoing a low-risk procedure. Chemoprophylaxis is typically reserved for patients at higher risk of VTE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumatic calf compression \u003C/strong\u003Eis already planned intra-operatively as part of the patient\u0027s care, so this option does not represent an additional measure. Extending its use post-operatively \u003Cstrong\u003Euntil discharge\u003C/strong\u003E would be unnecessary for this low-risk patient. Once able to mobilise, pneumatic calf compression may actually deter mobilisation due to the patient being fixed/attached to the pump device.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraduated compression stockings and enoxaparin daily for ten days after the operation\u003C/strong\u003E would be an overtreatment for this low-risk patient, potentially increasing the risk of bleeding complications without significant benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while hypercholesterolaemia is mentioned in the patient\u0027s history, its role as a risk factor for VTE is contentious. Some studies have suggested that elevated triglyceride levels may increase VTE risk, while high HDL cholesterol may decrease risk, but total cholesterol levels have not been consistently associated with VTE risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, for low-risk patients undergoing low-risk procedures like an elective inguinal hernia repair, mechanical prophylaxis with graduated compression stockings and intra-operative pneumatic calf compression is usually sufficient. The potential risks of chemoprophylaxis in such cases may outweigh the benefits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["No chemoprophylaxis is required for low-risk patients undergoing low-risk procedures.","The Caprini Score is a widely used and validated risk assessment model for venous thromboembolism in surgical patients."],"references":["Richardson WS, Hamad GG Stefanidis. VTE Prophylaxis for Laparoscopic Surgery Guidelines: An Update. Surg Endosc \u00a02017; 31:501-503. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28091748/","Guideline for the Prevention of Venous Thromboembolism (VTE) in Adult Hospitalised Patients. In: QLD health clinical practice guidelines [online]. Available at: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/clinical- practice/guidelines-procedures/medicines/safety"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38233"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"125"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38233"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-10T22:13:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-10T22:16:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"125"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52850"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups",